JOEL: do not spend any more time on this issue; automaid install is fine.

Q: Does my automaid utils.set_mseed_time_correction flip the proper activity
flag bit?

A: Yes.

I saved a normal output of automaid (bit flipped and value added to header) and
one without the bit flipped (but value still added to header) and then used
msmod to flip the bit -->

$ ~/programs/msmod/msmod --actflags 1,1 automaid_bit_not_flipped.mseed -o msmod_bit_flipped.mseed

* If we then inspect the `recordanalyzer` output for both (automaid vs msmod bit
  flipping) we see that in both cases "Activity flags: 2" (maybe it's a sum of
  `--actflags 1,1)?

$ diff -y --suppress-common-lines automaid_bit_flipped.recordanalyzer msmod_bit_flipped.recordanalyzer
FILE: automaid_bit_flipped.mseed				|       FILE: msmod_bit_flipped.mseed
        mu_sec: 40						|               mu_sec: 0
    Corrected Starttime: 2018-07-06T01:49:28.590640Z		|           Corrected Starttime: 2018-07-06T01:49:28.590600Z
FILE: automaid_bit_flipped.mseed				|       FILE: msmod_bit_flipped.mseed
FILE: automaid_bit_flipped.mseed				|       FILE: msmod_bit_flipped.mseed
FILE: automaid_bit_flipped.mseed				|       FILE: msmod_bit_flipped.mseed
FILE: automaid_bit_flipped.mseed				|       FILE: msmod_bit_flipped.mseed

* If we additionally inspect the records using libmseed,
  `~/programs/libmseed/example/mseedview`, you'll not the same 40 mu_sec diff in
  the purported starttimes of the first record (only) in the set, but if you use
  -vvv flag with mseedveiw you'll see that it says "Byte swapping needed for
  unpacking of header" so maybe that offset gets applied when header further
  unpacked? I don't know; nor do I care. Offset is 3 orders of mag smaller than
  our sampling interval.

$ diff -y --suppress-common-lines *mseedview       
FDSN:MH_P0006_00_B_D_H, 2, 4096, 1033 samples, 20.0071 Hz       |       FDSN:MH_P0006_00_B_D_H, 2, 4096, 1033 samples, 20.0071 Hz

So I'm content my version in automaid flips (only) the proper bit.
